<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-20T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-20T08:00:00-05:00" n="355" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2309</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MJVA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-20T21:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 20,
                                            1918, 9 p.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your telegram July 18, 5 p.m. Acting Minister for Foreign Affairs
                                assures me that the Chinese Government has no intention of
                                attempting to oust Russians from the control of the Chinese Eastern
                                Railway. He states however that two days ago such a course was
                                strongly urged upon the Foreign Office by a representative of “a
                                certain nation,” obviously meaning Japan.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_MJVA1"><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>